FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: Part IV, Section A, Line 2:
ExplntnTxt: The organization supports the NCMC Board of Trustees, which is not required to obtain recognition of exempt status because it is considered to be a governmental entity.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: Part IV, Section D, Line 3:
ExplntnTxt: The supported organization has a significant voice in the organization's investment policies and in directing the use of the organization's income or assets. All three of the representatives appointed by the supported organization are voting members of the organization's board of directors and participate in the decision-making process at the highest level. In addition, one representative of the supported organization serves on the Finance Committee, which generally oversees the operations and financial condition of the organization, including its investment policies. Two representatives of the supported organization serve on an internal committee which monitors adherence to any qualitative contractual requirements. No new debt is incurred by the organization without the approval of the supported organization. Lastly, the supported organization is given a significant voice in the conduct of the organization's affairs by virtue of its operating sublease with the organization.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: Part IV, Section E, Line 2a:
ExplntnTxt: The organization supports the NCMC Board of Trustees by contracting with Banner Health (an Arizona 501(c)(3) organization) to operate the North Colorado Medical Center. Under the terms of the contract, Banner Health System pays an annual use charge to the organization for hospital facilities, equipment and the business franchise. These funds, together with other cash reserves, are used by the organization to provide the North Colorado Medical Center with liquid working capital and funding for major and routine capital expenditures. The organization may borrow money to fund capital projects, which results in the organization servicing the debt incurred. In addition, the organization also provides grants to support local healthcare charities. Please see Schedule A, Part I, Line 11g for the amount of support provided. These activities directly further the exempt purpose of the organization, which is to provide quality healthcare at a reasonable cost to the North Colorado Medical Center service area.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: Part IV, Section E, Line 2b:
ExplntnTxt: If the organization did not conduct the activities described in Section E, line 2a, the supported organization would have to directly undertake the activities. The supported organization was formed to provide for healthcare needs of the region, which includes the availability of hospital facilities. The supported organization is providing for the healthcare needs of the region through the use of the organization and its activities.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART I, LINE 12G:
ExplntnTxt: SOMERVILLE HOSPITAL (THE "ORGANIZATION") IS A WHOLLY-OWNED SUBSIDIARY OF THE CAMBRIDGE PUBLIC HEALTH COMMISSION D/B/A CAMBRIDGE HEALTH ALLIANCE (CHA). CHA IS A GOVERNMENT ENTITY CREATED BY, AND CURRENTLY EXISTING PURSUANT TO, MASSACHUSETTS STATUTE, CHAPTER 147 OF THE ACTS AND RESOLVES OF 1996. NOTWITHSTANDING THE ORGANIZATION'S NAME, THE ORGANIZATION DOES NOT OPERATE ANY FACILITY THAT IS, OR IS REQUIRED TO BE, LICENSED, REGISTERED, OR SIMILARLY RECOGNIZED BY THE COMMONWEALTH OF MASSACHUSETTS. FACILITIES LOCATED ON REAL PROPERTY OWNED BY THE ORGANIZATION ARE OPERATED BY CHA. THE ORGANIZATION PROVIDES ITS FACILITIES TO CHA AT OR BELOW COST AND LEASES ITS EMPLOYEES TO CHA, SUCH EMPLOYEES BEING UNDER THE DIRECT CONTROL AND SUPERVISION OF CHA. CHA PAYS ALL EXPENSES INCURRED BY THE ORGANIZATION TO OPERATE ITS FACILITIES, INCLUDING THE COSTS OF ALL MAINTENANCE AND CAPITAL IMPROVEMENTS TO THESE FACILITIES. CHA REIMBURSES THE ORGANIZATION FOR LEASED EMPLOYEES AT FAIR MARKET VALUE. PART IV, SECTION A, LINE 2: THE ORGANIZATION'S SOLE SUPPORTED ORGANIZATION IS THE CAMBRIDGE PUBLIC HEALTH COMMISSION D/B/A CAMBRIDGE HEALTH ALLIANCE ("CHA"). CHA DOES NOT HAVE AN IRS DETERMINATION OF STATUS UNDER SECTION 509(A) (1) OR (2) OF THE INTERNAL REVENUE CODE (THE "CODE") BECAUSE IT IS A GOVERNMENTAL UNIT. CHA WAS CREATED IN 1996 BY CHAPTER 147 OF THE ACTS OF 1996 OF THE COMMONWEALTH OF MASSACHUSETTS (THE "ENABLING ACT") AS "A BODY POLITIC AND CORPORATE." IN THE ENABLING ACT, THE MASSACHUSETTS LEGISLATURE DECLARED, "[CHA] IS HEREBY CONSTITUTED A PUBLIC INSTRUMENTALITY AND THE EXERCISE BY [CHA] OF THE POWERS CONFERRED BY THIS ACT SHALL BE DEEMED AND HELD TO BE THE PERFORMANCE OF AN ESSENTIAL PUBLIC FUNCTION." THE ENABLING ACT FURTHER PROVIDES THAT CHA IS GOVERNED AND CONTROLLED BY A BOARD APPOINTED BY THE CITY MANAGER OF CAMBRIDGE. CONSEQUENTLY, CHA IS AN ORGANIZATION DESCRIBED IN SECTION 1701B) (1) (A) (V) AND, BY EXTENSION, SECTION 509(A) (1) OF THE CODE. BY LETTER TO THE ORGANIZATION DATED JULY 25, 2013, THE INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE STATED, "WE DETERMINED THAT YOU ARE A TYPE I SUPPORTING ORGANIZATION UNDER 509(A) (3). A TYPE I SUPPORTING ORGANIZATION IS OPERATED, SUPERVISED, OR CONTROLLED BY ONE OR MORE PUBLICLY SUPPORTED CHARITIES." THERE HAVE BEEN NO CHANGES TO CHA'S OPERATION, SUPERVISION, OR CONTROL OF THE ORGANIZATION SINCE JULY 25, 2013.

THEREFORE, THE COLLEGE HAS COMPLETED THE SUPPORT SCHEDULE IN PART II TO SUBSTANTIATE THAT IT MEETS THE PUBLIC SUPPORT TEST. THE COLLEGE CONTINUES TO QUALIFY AS A SCHOOL.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART IV, SECTION A, LINE 6:
ExplntnTxt: MISSISSIPPI BAPTIST HEALTH SYSTEMS, INC. PROVIDES LIMITED SUPPORT TO PUBLIC CHARITIES ON BEHALF OF ITS SUPPORTED ORGANIZATIONS. SUPPORT IS GIVEN TO PUBLIC CHARITIES THAT FURTHER THE PURPOSES OF MISSISSIPPI BAPTIST HEALTH SYSTEMS, INC., SUCH AS CANCER RESEARCH, SERVICES TO THE HOMELESS, MEDICAL EDUCATION, SERVICES PROVIDED TO THE NEEDY, WOMEN AND CHILDREN'S SERVICES, THE ELDERLY, AND HOME CARE AND HOSPICE. FUNDS ARE COLLECTED BY BAPTIST MEMORIAL HEALTH CARE FOUNDATION, INC. FOR ALL OF ITS RELATED ENTITIES AND THEN INVESTED AND DISPERSED AS DIRECTED BY THE SUPPORTED ORGANIZATIONS. PLEASE SEE SCHEDULE I, PART II FOR DONATIONS TO PUBLIC CHARITIES THAT FURTHER THE MISSION OF THE SUPPORTED ORGANIZATIONS.
